<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-128-994  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 128 994.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Jan 29 1990 n575 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bush to ease export rules? (the Bush Administration may loosenexport controls to the Eastern bloc)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robinson, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Bush Administration is being pressured by trading allies andUS industry to make trade with the Eastern bloc and CoComcountries easier by easing export limitations on computers,telecommunications products and other items.andP;  The 17-nationCoordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls (CoCom) maylose some of its influence as a result of the export restrictionchanges, and the US may find it more difficult to influenceEast-West technology trade as a result of the move.andP;  US firmsworry that they may lose out to manufacturers in other countriesshould they step up trade with the Eastern bloc.andP;  The fast pace ofpolitical change in the Eastern bloc since mid-1989 has increasedpressure on the government to loosen export controls, but theDefense Department is reluctant to make changes.andP;  The plans of theBush administration and industry reaction to possible changes arediscussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Political IssuesInternational TradeGovernment RegulationEastern EuropeTechnology TransferNational GovernmentComputer IndustryManufacturersCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Commerce Department applications for technology export processed:1989. (graph)Dollar value of computer exports to CoCom, East bloc, China, freeworld. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>